{
    "analysis": "Executor returned a compact summary of all telemetry files: metric.csv (148,984 rows) and trace.csv (34,636 rows) cover the full incident interval 2022-03-21 18:00–18:29 (UTC+8). metric.csv contains many per-service and per-pod KPIs (app.grpc.*, app.http.*, many runtime.java_lang_* JVM metrics). trace.csv contains per-route trace metrics (trace.self.*, trace.from_*, trace.to_*). log.csv has log.error_count and log.row_count. error_logs.csv contains raw messages for frontend and checkoutservice-2. From this, the next step is metric-based anomaly detection to narrow candidate faulty component-KPIs within the incident window. I will compute global thresholds on the full metric time series (per the rules) and then detect anomalies inside the incident time window to produce a compact ranked list of candidate component-KPI faults.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Load metric.csv. For every unique (cmdb_id, kpi_name) pair: 1) compute the global P95 threshold using the full available series for that pair (do NOT filter by time). 2) Then filter metric rows to the incident time window March 21, 2022 18:00:00 to 18:30:00 (UTC+8) and count how many rows in that window exceed the computed global P95. 3) For pairs with at least one exceedance, return a compact table limited to the top 20 pairs sorted by exceedance count (descending) containing: cmdb_id, kpi_name, global_p95, exceed_count_in_window, earliest_exceed_timestamp (the minimal timestamp in the window where value>p95), max_value_in_window, and total_rows_in_window. Also return the total number of distinct (cmdb_id,kpi_name) pairs scanned. Keep outputs concise and do not print full time series." }

{
    "analysis": "Executor scanned metric.csv and computed global P95 per (cmdb_id, kpi_name) pair (5,042 pairs). Within the incident window (2022-03-21 18:00–18:30 UTC+8) the top offending pairs each only had 2 samples above their global P95. Earliest exceed examples cluster around two sub-intervals: one near 18:14–18:16 and another near 18:26–18:28. This suggests two brief failure events rather than sustained faults. To localize root causes we need to (1) identify the exact minute(s) with the highest concentration of metric anomalies (across KPIs and components) to mark the candidate failure occurrence times, and (2) list the components (cmdb_id) that show anomalies at those minutes to narrow down candidate root-cause components for each failure. Traces and logs will be used after we identify the candidate minutes and components.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using metric.csv, recompute global P95 per (cmdb_id, kpi_name) over the full series (do NOT filter by time). Then filter metric rows to the incident window 2022-03-21 18:00:00 to 2022-03-21 18:30:00 (UTC+8). For each row in the window mark it as an exceedance if value > that pair's global P95. Produce two compact outputs: \n1) A per-minute summary (group by timestamp minute) returning the top 10 minutes sorted by total exceedance count (descending) with columns: timestamp, exceedance_count, distinct_cmdb_id_count. \n2) A per-cmdb_id summary for the whole window returning top 20 cmdb_id by total exceedance_count with columns: cmdb_id, exceedance_count, earliest_exceed_timestamp, latest_exceed_timestamp, distinct_kpi_count_exceeded. \nKeep outputs small and aggregated (no full time series)."
}

{
    "analysis": "Executor results show concentrated metric anomalies at two distinct minutes with the largest exceedance counts: 2022-03-21T18:14:00+08:00 (191 exceedances across 30 components) and 2022-03-21T18:29:00+08:00 (356 exceedances across 49 components). Many frontend pods and productcatalogservice/checkoutservice pods (and nodes) show high total exceedance counts across the 30-minute window, suggesting system-wide impact at multiple times. These per-minute peaks are the best candidates for the timestamps of the two failures. Next, we must determine which components at each peak show the most severe KPI deviations (not just count of KPIs exceeding P95) so we can focus trace and log analysis on likely root-cause components. I will therefore extract per-component anomaly details (which KPIs exceeded, and how severely) at each candidate minute to identify the most likely root-cause components for each failure.",
  "completed": "False",
  "instruction": "For metric.csv: 1) Recompute global P95 per (cmdb_id, kpi_name) over the full available series. 2) Filter metric rows to only the two candidate minutes: 2022-03-21T18:14:00+08:00 and 2022-03-21T18:29:00+08:00. 3) For each of those two minutes, produce a compact table of up to top 20 cmdb_id sorted by severity where severity = sum_over_exceeded_kpis((value - p95)/p95) (i.e., aggregated relative breach). For each returned cmdb_id include: cmdb_id, exceedance_count (how many KPIs exceeded at that minute), severity (as defined), distinct_kpi_names_exceeded_count, and a list of up to top 5 exceeded KPI entries formatted as (kpi_name, value, global_p95, relative_breach=(value-p95)/p95). 4) Also return a brief per-minute summary line with timestamp, total_exceedance_count, distinct_cmdb_id_count, and top_cmdb_id_by_severity. Keep all outputs compact and limit lists as requested." }

{
    "analysis": "Executor identified two distinct anomaly peaks in metrics within the incident window: a spike at 2022-03-21T18:14:00+08:00 dominated by checkoutservice-related components (checkoutservice2-0 highest severity) and a larger spike at 2022-03-21T18:29:00+08:00 dominated by adservice-related components (adservice2-0 highest severity). Metric exceedances alone suggest two brief failure events (one around 18:14 and one around 18:29) with many components affected at those minutes. To localize root causes we must now use traces to determine which services/pods were the most downstream faulty components in request call chains at those minutes (trace data can show elevated self.duration_p95, error_rate, or upstream->downstream route delays) and then use logs/error_logs to confirm resource-level reasons. Traces are the next best source to disambiguate which service/pod is the root cause among multiple metric-faulty candidates.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Load trace.csv. 1) For every unique (cmdb_id, trace_name) compute the global P95 over the full available series (do NOT filter by time). 2) Filter trace rows to only the two candidate minutes: 2022-03-21T18:14:00+08:00 and 2022-03-21T18:29:00+08:00. 3) For each of those two minutes produce a compact table of up to top 20 cmdb_id sorted by the number of trace metrics exceeding their global P95 at that minute. For each returned cmdb_id include: cmdb_id, exceed_count (how many trace_names exceeded), list_of_exceeded_traces (limit to top 10 entries) where each entry is (trace_name, value, global_p95, relative_breach=(value-p95)/p95), and a short indicator if any of the exceeded traces are error_rate or trace.self.duration_p95/self.duration_mean. 4) Also return a one-line per-minute summary with timestamp, total_exceedance_count (sum across all cmdb_ids), distinct_cmdb_id_count, and top_cmdb_id_by_exceed_count. Keep outputs compact and limit lists as requested (no full time series)." }

{
    "analysis": "Previous steps computed global P95 thresholds and found two sharp metric anomaly peaks at 2022-03-21T18:14:00+08:00 (checkoutservice-dominated severity, checkoutservice2-0 top) and 2022-03-21T18:29:00+08:00 (larger, adservice/productcatalog/frontend-impact, adservice2-0 top). Trace analysis showed frontends had many exceeded per-route traces; traces with error_rate and trace.self.duration_* were present at both minutes. Log and error_logs analysis showed strong corroboration for frontend pods: frontend-2 appears in traces, logs, and error_logs at 18:14, and all three frontends (frontend-0/1/2) appear in all three sources at 18:29 (many error log warnings like 'failed to retrieve...'). Metric severity for checkoutservice2-0 at 18:14 was huge driven by mesh/jaeger metrics, suggesting heavy instrumentation/mesh traffic or mis-measured tiny baselines producing large relative breaches. To decide root cause component and underlying reason for each failure, we must confirm which resource KPIs (CPU, memory, disk I/O, network, process, etc.) of candidate components show clear resource-level faults at the exact minute of the failure. Specifically, we need the metric-level exceeded KPIs at the two minutes for the top candidate components (frontends, checkoutservice*, adservice*, productcatalogservice* instances, and implicated nodes) to determine whether the root cause is a container resource issue (CPU/memory/IO/network), node-level resource issue, or an application-level error. The next step is therefore to extract the metric exceedances (value > global P95) at those two minutes for a focused set of components and summarize which KPI types are most frequently and severely breached.",
  "completed": "False",
  "instruction": "Load metric.csv and compute global P95 per (cmdb_id, kpi_name) using the full available series (do NOT filter by time). Then filter metric rows to the two exact minutes: 2022-03-21T18:14:00+08:00 and 2022-03-21T18:29:00+08:00. For the following cmdb_ids: [frontend-0, frontend-1, frontend-2, checkoutservice2-0, checkoutservice-0, checkoutservice-1, checkoutservice-2, adservice2-0, adservice2, adservice, productcatalogservice-0, productcatalogservice-1, productcatalogservice-2, productcatalogservice2-0, node-1, node-2, node-3, node-4, node-6], return: \n1) All metric rows (limit 200) at those minutes where value > corresponding global_p95, with columns: minute_timestamp, cmdb_id, kpi_name, value, global_p95, relative_breach=(value-p95)/p95. Sort the returned rows by minute_timestamp then descending relative_breach. \n2) A compact aggregated summary per minute that counts how many of the returned exceedances fall into broad KPI categories (use kpi_name prefix buckets: starting token before first '.' e.g., 'system', 'app', 'runtime', 'mesh', 'mesh.destination', etc.) and list the top 5 KPI-name-prefix buckets by count and by total relative_breach sum for each minute. \nKeep outputs bounded (max 200 raw rows, and small aggregated summaries)."
}

{
    "analysis": "We have followed the prescribed workflow: computed global P95 thresholds on full series, filtered the incident window (2022-03-21 18:00–18:30 UTC+8), detected two distinct anomaly minutes (2022-03-21T18:14:00+08:00 and 2022-03-21T18:29:00+08:00), and narrowed candidate components with metrics, traces, and logs. Findings so far: (1) 18:14 is dominated by extreme mesh.* metric breaches on checkoutservice pods (checkoutservice2-0, checkoutservice-0, checkoutservice-1, checkoutservice-2) — many mesh.destination global P95s are zero producing infinite relative breaches — while frontend-2 also shows trace/log/error entries at 18:14. (2) 18:29 is a larger spike affecting many components but is strongly corroborated across traces, logs, and error_logs for frontend-0/1/2; node metrics (node-2 and node-6) also show notable system CPU/I/O breaches at 18:29. According to localization rules, when multiple container/service-level components are faulty, the root cause is typically the most downstream faulty component in traces; when node-level faults appear, compare significance and counts. At present, 18:14 is ambiguous between checkoutservice pods (very high mesh metric severity) and frontend-2 (trace/log/error signals); 18:29 is strongly pointing at frontends, but node-level system metrics indicate a possible node resource issue contributing to frontend failures. To resolve the ambiguity we need targeted, compact evidence tying resource-level faults to the candidate components at each minute. Specifically, for the first failure we should confirm which checkoutservice pod (if any) shows its first metric fault exactly at or before 18:14, and whether that pod also exhibits trace.self errors or error_logs at that minute. That will let us determine the root cause component and reason for the 18:14 failure. The 18:29 failure will be analyzed next after we finalize 18:14.",
  "completed": "False",
  "instruction": "Using the precomputed global P95 thresholds (compute them over the full metric series if not already available), focus on the checkoutservice pods: [checkoutservice2-0, checkoutservice-0, checkoutservice-1, checkoutservice-2]. Within the incident window (2022-03-21 18:00:00 to 18:30:00 UTC+8), for each of these pods: \n1) Find the earliest timestamp in the window when any metric (any kpi_name) exceeds that pod-KPI's global P95. Return a compact row per pod with: cmdb_id, earliest_exceed_timestamp, total_exceeded_kpis_at_that_minute (count), and the top KPI by relative breach at that minute (kpi_name, value, global_p95, relative_breach). Limit to these 4 pod rows. \n2) For each pod's earliest_exceed_timestamp (from step 1), check trace.csv at that exact minute for that pod: if any trace_name among trace.self.duration_mean/p95 or trace.self.error_rate exceeds its trace-level global P95, return those trace rows (trace_name, value, global_p95, relative_breach). Limit to top 10 trace rows total. \n3) Also return whether error_logs.csv contains any entries for that pod within that same minute (boolean) and the count of error_log rows for that pod in that minute. \nKeep all outputs concise and bounded (<= 4 pod summary rows, <= 10 trace rows, and per-pod error_log counts)."
}

